An extreme push: MP3 players against mobiles.
You will be advised, how to choose
While almost all mobiles can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can call.
It seems clear that it is better to buy only one phone.
There is no shortage of reasons for obtaining an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the manner of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for the house a cheap high-end gramphone to put the new Maxim Turbulenc album.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl disk, and from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
Now, if there are stuffed vinyl discs in your shelves, with rock art, jazz or blues, you're probably dreaming of such a gramphone.
The same is true of music during travel, namely compressed music, to say it in a simplified way - music in MP3.
Here too, there are categories depending on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand krona on a reader, just as a Pink Floyd fan would have difficulty holding listeners purchased for twenty krona on the market.
These are two extremes, among which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
The life of the batteries is also decisive
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than simply reading music, but these are unknown functions, of course, of most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
Alongside the first functions, phone calls and texting, he is able to read music and movies, record them, he has a variable quality camera and can, for example, serve to navigation.
And if you take Smartphones and communicators into account, you'll have a small computer in your pocket.
Since no refrigerator knows how to grill meat and no TV will take photographs, we are almost witnessing a miracle.
However, the universal character of the mobile is not without disadvantages.
The larger the number of functions you use, the more the interval between two refills will be reduced.
And music reading is one of the most important energy wastes.
Mobiles that are able to read music for 10 to 12 hours are rare, in most cases this figure is significantly lower.
In this regard, music readers (especially the most rudimentary) are much more performing.
In the case of cheap mobiles, count on them playing music for only a few hours.
If, in addition, you have to call from time to time, get, to be sure, a second charge for the job - this being even valid for the more expensive devices.
The problem will not arise for MP3 players, who are capable of continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the least performing.
Another problem occurs when recording music on the mobile.
Unfortunately, that a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, especially since not all can be directly connected to the computer without special software.
You can, of course, record music directly on the memory card, but few card readers know to take themselves without a reduction, given the tiny dimensions of memory cards used in mobiles.
With regard to readers, you do not need any software except iPod.
Just fill in, through the USB connector, the music device from the computer.
Most mobiles and readers will themselves create a media library classified by the name of the performer, the title of the album, style, or then by the judgment of the user.
Some devices only display an index that has a tree structure, in the way of Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (river, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobiles have more know-how
In choosing a concrete device, be particularly interested in the lifespan of the accumulator, the memory capacity, the quality and the type of output of the sound and, of course, the ease of the order.
If music is for you, essentially, a background noise and if in the day you will listen to it for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you just need any mobile reading the MP3.
Virtually all the mobiles are now capable of them.
You don't even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or the player is capable of reading.
Everyone gets to read the MP3s and the vast majority of the music that will reach you just this format.
It is one of the most common formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices also read WMA music.
The AAC (format used by the Apple firm and its iPods) is less common.
High-end mobiles also allow, for example, the purchase of online music.
Simply visit the corresponding web pages (or those of another provider) and buy the song or album in question from the mobile phone.
This service alone should be a convincing reason for obtaining a musical mobile.
Unfortunately, operators' offer is miserable and, in most cases, it is limited to fast-made tubes.
The prices are not even the lowest.
However, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (either via GSM, the Internet or even the wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their motive on their own.
Every time you want to listen to something, you just have to get the mobile out of your pocket, while you forgot your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you always have listeners or a handsfree with connection.
If this is not the case, you can use the built-in enclosures, which have almost all the mobiles, but a minimum of MP3 readers.
For many, the main advantage of musical furniture is their price.
The least expensive normally costs less than three thousand.
For a price of three thousand kroner, we can have a walkman already very convenient.
In most cases, however, you will be limited by the absence of output for ordinary listeners.
The price of the best phones and the best tools, also equipped with an entrance for ordinary listeners, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy order.
Really anyone comes to order the most rudimentary readers - which do not necessarily correspond to the least expensive (see our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the similarity of the command with that of a cassette post, commonly used in the past, or a gramphone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a random connected mobile internet, followed by a huge data transmission bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobiles (e.g. Vodafone 527) generally have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (type M2, microSD, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
Basic models generally only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive get out even with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or a iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you do not have to spend more than 1 100 kroner.
If you are one of the most demanding auditors, choose specialized mobile walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent control keys for MP3, and thus the ease of the command is closer to that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose mobiles in the walkman series have the same user menu as MP3 players sold separately, is the one that went the further in this field.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and a lifetime of the accumulator (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours), is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the above mentioned brands.
A first virtual operator will win Czechia this year itself.
Maybe
The mobile market in Chechnya is relatively advanced, our operators offering practically the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force classic operators to lower prices.
Maybe he won't miss it for long.
We have already repeatedly mentioned on Mobil.cz the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
ČTÚ (The Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of an SMS was higher in our homes than in the rest of the Union, confirmed it.
Thus, following the last steps of the European Commission in the area of regulating roaming fees, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be for some customers of Czech mobile operators less expensive than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in Chechnya remain so high, compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really like to get into the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that far exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this regard, Pavel Dvořák, the President of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), who has repeatedly stated that there is no longer room for another operator in Chechnya, makes a chorus with the operators.
It is probably true that a classic operator with his own network seems to have no more chance (in fact, now he would find only difficult frequencies).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that has led to a considerable decrease in prices, which should subsequently also respond to conventional operators.
However, even before the entry of the riots such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the market, voices similar to those heard today in our homes were heard in Britain.
However, it appeared that there was room for such operators and that they could have real success.
We are not obliged to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch, in Poland, of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator managed to earn more than 100 thousand customers and become the country's fifth operator.
Let's add that behind Mobilking, there is the Penta financial group, which has among other things the U:fon in Czechia.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility to focus on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be effective, they actually need much less customers than a classic operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the relatively high construction, operation and maintenance costs of the mobile network.
In this way, in the world, virtual operators are profiled as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often offset by a limited service offer.
For example Tesco Mobile offers SMS at least twice as expensive in Britain as its competitors.
But, as shown by the example of Mobilking in Poland, targeting an unusual target group can also be a good publicity blow.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
"The real men choose Mobilking - an operator that they like and they can trust," said David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, exploiting this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept could also work at home.
Miroslav Čepický, vodafone's spokesperson, doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
All the more so as it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the provision of services."
In Chechnya, no chance, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in Chechnya, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this project successfully, but in Chechnya negotiations are not very supportive.
Rather, the launch of Mobilking will take place in other countries in our area," said in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, spokesman for the Penta financial group.
It therefore indirectly confirmed that the operators in Chechnya were, in any case, not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do their best so that a potential competitor may not appear.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the area of business customers, does not hide, for quite a long time, its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We tend to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telecommunications services but also mobile.
And the sooner it'll be the best.
We have already held negotiations on this possibility on several occasions with all the Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have been able to move forward in the negotiations," said the spokesman of the Pavel Kaidl group.
So the future is perhaps promising.
According to non-official information, it seems that we might be able to host the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
But for now, its creation is accompanied by total silence.
"At the moment, we do not think there is room on the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is compared to other very specific ones.
At the moment, no topic with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," said Vladimil Sršeň of the press department of Telefonika O2, in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also relate to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile Martina Kemrová's spokesperson states in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not registered for the viable and bilaterally advantageous project now, which could serve as a basis."
And she adds: "It is practically excluded that a virtual operator appears in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a limited period of time, we should now have a concrete agreement."
Vodafone rather directs its attention to the fulfilment of requests to obtain its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický said in this regard: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
This, we believe, means the most input from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is the discovery of a partner to establish a common network for a fast mobile internet."
Responsible authorities: in phase with operators
The mobile operators' approach is easily understandable, another operator's entry would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and thus to a decrease in their profits.
So how can we facilitate the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, operators know how to feel like fair larrons. The Chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon also testifies.
The most apparent pressure on the U:fon was the one exercised by the T-Mobile company at the time of the creation of the U:fon.
This shows information that is accessible to the public from the websites of ČTÚ.
Today, the U:fon is willing to use as an argument not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted in this regard: "Competition on the mobile market has also recently been enhanced by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the character of the mobile market in RT, it is clear that the entry of an additional player would subject it, and especially its services, to high requirements."
But given the attitude of mobile operators here, the indifference of Czech regulatory bodies seems to be disconcerting.
However, it is not only the attitude of ČTU, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in the economic competition in Chechnya.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
However, the latter adopts, in the face of this problem, its typical position.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the relevant virtual operator concerning the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been concluded for the time being, as the offer of potential stakeholders has not a priori presented sufficient interest for conventional operators," said Kristián Chalupa, the UUOHS Department of External Relations.
Such a statement would not surprise operators' representatives.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers, and on the other hand also take care that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, such a statement is more than misleading.
Especially since Kristián Chalupa adds: "In abroad, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a decrease in the prices of mobile telephone services."
However, pressure in the sense of an honest functioning of the market and a decrease in prices does not appear to be part of the UOHS' interests.
What is actually shocking is the almost touching agreement of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question, if it really is a coincidence, naturally arises.
Similarly, a strictly identical price of gasoline for all service stations is likely to be due to the chance and the hard fight of competition.
"The Office has not identified signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this regard, so it has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators have a dominant position, therefore none of them have an increased responsibility for their behaviour on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably missing even the Telecommunication Regulator," said Chaloupa.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications constitute, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators have a dominant position on such a market.
However, some law experts propose another view of things: in order for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, the consent of the network operator must be obtained at all times.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on its network.
This is how he necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of his activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the UOHS that three mobile operators proceed visibly in a similar way.
However, complaints from many interested parties (including GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Restoring responsibility on the ČTU is a fairly common turn in communications, through which the UOHS washes its hands.
We have already met this kind of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to introduce the recent development of the Telecommunications Act, an expansion of ČTÚ's powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised to improve the situation.
However, the UOHS representatives must know very well, but their interests seem to be elsewhere.
When no one looks, it can work.
That said, the operation of some kind of virtual pseudo operators, several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies publishing their own price lists of mobile telephone services, but they are only partially public.
In most cases, companies are involved in multi-level marketing.
Specific mobile telephone services are provided, for example, by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms generally reach only elected persons.
The magic tower consists of the fact that the company does in front of the operator is a classic business client, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important client, it obtains special (and other) price offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a resale.
"If what you're talking about happened, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions that we would consider and which could lead to a cessation of collaboration with the society in question," responded to our question regarding this problem Martina Kemrová.
However, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such an activity would not have reached the task of mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, they may be thousands of customers.
No operator, however, decides against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these companies bring them non-negligible benefits, and at the same time, as opposed to real virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický indicates possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however, the services of these companies are used only by a percentage of negligible customers.
In addition, they are obliged to admit that the SIM card on their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the way of ordinary customers of mobile operators."
This is precisely what should seem strange to ČTÚ.
In addition, there is another question in UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes on such a procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the UOHS has relatively broad powers to reveal such an activity, and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the operators' explanations, which claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions forbidding it.
When we are no longer the most expensive country
As we have mentioned several times before, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has resulted in a considerable decrease in the price of services.
However, practically in all the countries where virtual operators appeared, conventional operators were trying, sometimes more, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market too small, even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
It is precisely at this level that regulatory bodies have intervened in developed countries, which were defending not the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Both through formal measures and through informal pressure, they ended up getting the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators are dealing with this issue in the way a hot potato is being disposed of by transmitting it to a nearby target.
As a result of the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in skills is more beneficial to them.
But let's not throw the sleeve after the cognane.
If the flow information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear in our home, the Czech mobile market may be moving back.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the UOHS will be unable only to remain impassable in the face of the rejection (to discrimination) of other interested parties.
And maybe we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on Czech nationality day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the Kde dosov national anthem (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem was recorded again by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo singing, an interpretation with choir and an instrumental version.
The song is provided by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jérémieáš and Jaroslav Krček are the authors of the anthem arrangements.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek views Czech national singing as one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously entrusted Český rozhlas (Czech public radio), he chose for the interpretation of solo versions of singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I was trying to take care that both singers and the choir had a good saying, so that we could understand the words well, that they sang simultaneously," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate, next year, its 175th anniversary.
The Kde domov song was first played in 1834 on the stavovské divadlo boards (the State Theatre) in Fidlovačka (Kermesse des savetiers), a Czech original piece by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by music by František Škroup.
It has become popular and people have spontaneously made it appropriate.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first couple naturally became an integral part of the national anthem.
It remained one of seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
