The Sudets were calling for a referendum in the USA.
The Germans of the South asked in 1945 for Šumava to be integrated into the United States.
This stems from a letter filed in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna (The Scientific Library of the Southern Bohème).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, at least we want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, certain groups of South Germans allegedly addressed the President of the United States with such a desire.
This comes from, among other things, a preserved letter in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
Germans of Český Krumlov in the letter ask the American President not to allow "šumavská župa" (forest region south of Bohemian territory) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation very well and we want to be very sure that the words proclaiming that American troops come into German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," is written in the letter, "People, to whom the fate of Šumava is at the heart."
Given that the association with Czechoslovakia is allegedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only of brutality, disrespectful attitude, misunderstanding, oppression and bondage, the authors of the letter urge the American President to take into his hands the protectorate of Šumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe, that you would give this territory to a foreign state to us, that oppresses and destroys minorities and that did not at all contribute to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of the fourth million inhabitants," the letter says.
The alleged reason the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of "Czech oppressors".
If the President of the United States doubted the Germans' opinion of Šumava, he would have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to determine whether his inhabitants wanted to be part of the United States, or to live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, in view of the current knowledge of the post-war history, seem somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it well illustrates the expectations of the Germans of the Sudets of the day.
While the Czech Germans had to at least find out that the question of their expulsion from the Republic would arise, very few of them had such an opportunity.
Some were waiting for the United States and Great Britain to obtain a certain type of autonomy for the South.
Others believed that they would simply remain in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirmed this.
During the war, he was, as German of České Budějovice, engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
At the end of the war, he was captured by the English and placed in the Holstein region's catch camp, dozens of Czech Germans came to see him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that once they returned home, the Czech would benefit them," said Chalupa.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war thought that he would be expelled from the Republic following decrees Beneš.
