Rats also have sensations
A rat or a safe escape in the face of danger, does that mean he also feels fear?
Neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced of this: many animals also have sensations.
But how could it be verified that he experiences the same thing when he behaves in the same way as we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles answers to the question "What do you think you are true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else has so far been able to prove it just as one cannot prove that other human beings have a conscience.
But in that case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the issues of feeling or in general consciousness, we enter difficult terrains because Hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, he does the same thing as many other animals: he does death, escape or attack.
Human beings behave the same way, which is why some scientists deduce a comparable subjective life.
However, I do not believe that.
Two aspects of the structure of the brain make the transposition of our subjective life to that of the animals difficult.
One aspect is that circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the Prefrontal Side Cortex (because of its participation in the short-term memory and management and enforcement functions).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and appears to be completely absent in other beings.
So at least for these aspects of our consciousness that depends on the Prefrontal Cortex, among which the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being differs even from the other primates.
Another significant characteristic could be the linguistic nature of Man: a large part of his existence is related to language, which often means that his consciousness depends on him.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness was not to depend on language, it would surely influence it, so that animal consciousness, whatever its form, would probably differ much from most of our states of consciousness.
That is why it is so difficult to determine what consciousness can look like in other animals.
If this, internal and subjective, does not allow itself to be measured or, because of this particular Hardware, to analyze on the basis of our own experience, then its observation poses major problems.
Most of my developments refer to the content of the conscious life, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more easily accessed scientifically.
