No heels, no outer garments.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, freed from all tensions to obtain the relaxed appearance of man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
The other one, the person.
Inseparable except in intimacy, in these unknown moments of the general public, where one discovers intimate gestures and stolen glances of artists who do not care to get on stage.
German Günther Bauer blends in "Flamenco - people" the theatre of some performances with singers, dancers and guitarists with this less-known side of artists.
In this project, the photographer takes up the particular iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the Flemish Photography Month programming, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, greater every day", explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "may be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that these are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "in the street" are artists able to transmit on stage passion, sadness, joy ... by captivating the public.
To capture moments of personality of these artists you don't need to take pictures on stage.
They have a unique personality and character.
What interests me was to create an intimate atmosphere that allows me to capture with the camera the moments of personalities of the flamenco stars."
With the festival "People's Song of Mines", Bauer began a long trip in 1997 to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a plaque camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of the camera and the equipment, remind the classic photography.
The implementation of various stylistic means breaks with the classic side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day".
It is not dance or singing in itself, but the personality and character of the artist who captured the public with his art.
The search for the essentials and magic was the constant of this work presented these days at the El Fotómata gallery.
Flamenco stars like Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy photographed artists.
The project has become an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a gallery portrait collection book.
The passion for Bauer's portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of old sportsmen" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves photographing the portrait of people, knowing them and being able to enter their lives for a moment or less long.
I think in photography the portrait is the most difficult kind.
You're standing in front of people, characters you don't know, or they just leave you a few minutes to take a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true."
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco called "Flamenco - people", is exhibited at the Galerie El Fotómata, located at number 20 of rue de la Mata (the road parallel to the Peupleraie d'Hercule) which will be opened until 16 October next.
