The first time this happens, it may surprise you, but in reality it doesn't matter.
It's a benign sleep disorder called sleepwalking.
This is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
Sure there's more than one talking during the night.
This phenomenon may occur very sporadicly (once in life for example associated with a severe fever episode), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance
They are often related to other sleeping disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, night sickness (drinking in bed) or sleepwalking, but this is not always the case.
As we have already said before, they can also be associated with very severe fevers, stress situations or overexcitation.
Anyway, it's a little studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
He may speak with a quiet little voice, with isolated words, murmurs or on the contrary with screams, cries, long speeches ...
In the event that sleepwalking becomes very frequent, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist, to check if there is a problem that causes much anxiety and to get an explanation to this problem.
We said it's a benign alteration, which is why there's no treatment, unless it's related to another sleep disorder that can be cured (for example, if it's related to sleep apnea or stress).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to sleep.
Therefore find quiet games and avoid television programs or series that are more or less violent.
With very nervous children who have trouble relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm down internally.
This will allow the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
As soon as the dreams appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he won't remember what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him.
It's useless because he's unconscious and you'd wake him up.
Even if he speaks, he sleeps and so rests.
Remember that if he is very anxious several times, he is advised to consult a doctor or to check what causes such anxiety in the child.
If you understand what it says (which is not usual), do not be tempted to question it for information.
You won't get anything, because he's sleeping, he's not aware to be able to organize his thinking.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you will not know what he is dreaming about, so be careful how you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw from it.
Never tell the child that you can question him during the night to find out his secrets.
Not even kidding.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
In conclusion, don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
