Interview - Blood returned safe
Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday the 10th anniversary of his foundation, and his president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice because Hema-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
And above all, he regained the confidence of the public who had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this tragedy and public outcry, in February 1994, the Government of Canada instituted a public investigation, chaired by Justice Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances leading to such a tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a disaster would not happen again.
While Judge Krever was late in filing his report, some provinces then established a committee with the aim of planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Hema-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and territories.
"In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, only 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalled.
The situation was discouraging.
In an effort to improve the safety of blood products and work in the field during the years that followed, we regained public confidence," she said proudly, saying that by the beginning of 2008, almost 94 per cent of the Quebec population now had confidence in Hema-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary maintains that "confidence is something extremely fragile".
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, many cases of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, were seen in Europe, reports the one that has been holding the fort since its founding in 1998.
"And we didn't know at all whether this disease could be transmitted by blood.
It was then based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, that when it is not known and that a serious disease can result from it, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that is characterized by brain degeneration leading inevitably to death, exclusion measures are introduced.
Thus, in April 1999, the blood of those who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980 was refused.
A few years ago, however, it was demonstrated beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle applied had meaning."
In 1999 a much more sensitive technique of HIV testing appeared on the market: nucleic acid (TAN) tests that enable direct detection in donor blood of the presence of the virus itself and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used so far were based.
The TANs allowed to shorten the mute period, which extends between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than one week.
This has significantly reduced the risk that some donors will be infected without knowledge and cannot be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
"In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of transmission of HIV by a blood product occurs.
I believe that today we can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health," says the head of the management of Hema-Québec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of the Meeting, which, like the West Nile virus, was transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant," Dr. Décary continues before stressing that in addition to a secure supply, Hema-Québec must also provide sufficient supplies.
"The needs are increasing because the population is ageing.
As anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a red blood cell or platelet recharge.
The ageing of the population also has implications for the blood donor network, which averages only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation."
Any person who is 18 years of age and over who meets the eligibility criteria may, however, give blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14 per cent of those who offer their blood are not accepted, because they are infected with AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where malaria occurs, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
The shortages are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this donor network as they grow old and can no longer give their blood.
However, it is difficult to convince people to give their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Today's life being so scary, we rarely find time to spend an hour giving of his blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec provides not only blood products but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eye globes and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These fabrics are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public cordon blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered a biomedical waste is filled with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukaemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the banking of our thousandth sample of cordon blood and are expected to be taken more than a thousand a year.
We should begin to propose these for grafts early next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this program of cordon blood collection as very popular.
"More mothers are disappointed not to have access to it," because Hema-Québec does not have the means to propose this complex and costly program in all hospitals in Quebec.
