In its September 17, issue, Le Duvoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Canadian Mining Vice-President Barrick Gold.
Continuing an Orwellian logic, the author claims that the largest gold company in the world has attempted a defamation of six million against three authors and a small publishing house without the sound in order to launch a "transparent public debate".
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of prosecution in defamation, but the law.
Without surprise, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by Mr. Garver.
Because, for Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to lead to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to hiss?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and the editor of the Black Canada book will have to spend considerable amounts in order to prepare their defence and to fight, to very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by almost bottomless pockets of the mine.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly settlement that will undermine the opposition in addition to defrauding anyone who dares to look at the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was in public opinion that she should have presented her vision of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, discussions in Canada are normally done through the exchange of ideas rather than with a matraque.
It was therefore sufficient for the mine to open its books, records and to establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust public opinion and rejects petitions and letters of support to Black Canada authors.
Perhaps Mr Garver could explain how he can both ask for a "public" debate while disregarding the views of that same audience?
In the world of the vice-president, it seems that this word refers only to paid fat lawyers and not to all Canadians; this is a rather close view of the concept.
In democracy, even detractors have the right to speak.
What he doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - Barrick Gold, is that the public who supports Black Canada's authors and publishers does so primarily because he rejects the brutal way of mining.
This audience is prepared to hear and judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not in the context of what many perceive as a prosecution-baillon (following the "public debate", Barrick Gold has also just filed a stand-up for Black Canada's authors urging them to stop using this term...).
Beyond Mr Garver's surreal speech, Barrick Gold's pursuit is a direct attack on freedom of academic research and the quest for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It also denies the right to cite credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which are the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss matters that disturb wealthy businesses in this world in a country like Canada, under repeated prosecution, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, he could do so by following the scientific standards used by Black Canada's authors.
She has a right to reply.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's excessive prosecution clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the academic world, as well as for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place mechanisms limiting this kind of abusive prosecution.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the US $700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has been shaking Wall Street for months still has to be endorsed by both Congress Chambers.
It includes: improved monitoring by the electors of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for default of payment, as well as a right to look at wages paid to the managers of the relief companies.
US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, President of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday, after a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done in such a way as to protect the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"This is the fundamental point: if we don't do this, the trauma, chaos and disturbances on the American daily life will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had been on the sprint in the last few hours, fearing the effect of a new failure on the mood of investors.
The deadline for opening the markets this morning was agreed.
Lately associated with the negotiations, the two candidates for the U.S. presidential election were rather in favour of the agreement, but they did not fail to express their dissatisfaction that we were obliged to reach this end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama attributed himself to the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, including that aimed at allowing owners to keep their home and that on the salary of the leaders of the companies that were rescued by the state.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to be congratulated.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on the U.S. television waves.
Asked on another chain to see if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent John McCain replied, "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The main lines I have read [show] that it is something that we will all have to digest and with which we will be able to move forward.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable," he said.
The 700 billion plan aims to buy with taxpayers' money the doubtful, risky and unsaleable debts of the American financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the outbreak of a real estate bubble which has first led to the collapse of mortgage-at-risk (subprimary) credits before extending to other more widespread forms of credit securities (CPAA) and leading to a freeze on liquidity and the disruption of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republicans who had the first draft of the deal capped last week.
It is believed that this impasse has been lifted since Democrats have accepted that certain "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are only secured by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to round out the angles for everyone at Congress, a provision was also added that if the government was to take five years' losses with this program, it could introduce new taxes to help it recover its delivery.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first instalment of 250 billion to which another 100 billion may be added if the President deems it necessary.
Another 350 billion should be paid by another Congress vote.
In exchange for his assistance, Washington will be able to obtain participations in the relief companies that will pay him dividends in case of profit and that he will be able to resell when the torment is over.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay the seizure procedures for housing related to the real estate loans involved in this plan, as well as to set limits on the remuneration and departure allowances paid to the managers of the affected businesses.
The architects of the plan would like to see him put to the vote of the House of Representatives today, and to the vote of the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plans will have the green fire.
In fact, votes continued to rise yesterday against this project, both in the republican and democratic camp.
"Of course, Washington is not listening to you," said Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, to his constituents.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that is to take advantage of taxpayers."
Animator of a small group at the Congress called "the caucus of the sceptics", the Democratic representative Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred eminent economic teachers, including three Nobel Prizes, have written to tell us: Congress is asked not to hurry and carefully examine the way forward," he said yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again evidence of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for EUR 11.2 billion (16.3 billion US).
The intervention by the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas reported that it had refused to acquire its competitor in full shipwreck since it had lost EUR 2 billion (US 2.9 billion) in the risk real estate loan crisis in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and ten largest insurers.
"This is not lost money," said Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos yesterday.
In return, a right to vote in the bank and influence is recovered.
It is precisely something that savings and households now appreciate the uncertain announcement of time."
Meanwhile, on the other side of the Channel, the British government seemed to be in the process of nationalizing another bank damaged by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take into account all ongoing loans from Bradford and Bringley, of which more than $41.5 billion (US$75.5 billion) of real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it was the one who would buy the British bank's branches and customer accounts.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
