What could have made Zuschlag &amp; Company in their invoice factory?
Soon, on October 8, the hearings related to the ongoing criminal proceedings will begin against János Zuschlag and his accomplices.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of fraud, in the form of a criminal organization, on a permanent and regular basis, which has caused particularly significant damage.
According to the prosecutor's office, the money from grants was spent for personal purposes, while the benefits were justified by false invoices.
The state and municipalities' money, about 65 million HUF, was going on the one hand in the cassettes of the Fair Baloldal movement and on the other hand in the pocket of some people.
Their method, also made public by the investigating authorities, was to pay the money of the subsidies obtained by issuing invoices of fees, behind which no actual benefit was provided and thus, the associations never complied with their commitments.
According to the indictment, much of the invoices were false.
For the latter, they made invoice books in the Józsefváros market, while they made the stamps in Kiskunhalas.
For the names of companies to be included in the invoices, it was decided, among other things, during the tour in the northern province of Lake Balaton, carried out by István Lados, at the request of János Zuschlag.
According to the latter's statement, he had to find pensions and restaurants.
For his personal consumption, he requested an invoice, on the basis of which they made the other invoices that they were going to introduce, inter alia, with the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, as well as the City of Capital to access grants.
The majority of the invoices were created by István Lados and his accomplice András ★ri, who, according to our information, was mainly concerned with drafting the files necessary for obtaining the grants.
One of Lados' choices was a bistro during a search circuit.
According to the two invoices issued by the Zuschlag in 2003, this place ensured the restoration of a group of 90 people, members of the association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
However, according to the manager, it would have been impossible for so many people to occupy this place at the same time.
Similarly, in the summer of 2002, the invoice established on behalf of the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, which will subsequently bear the name of Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, grew up with defects of form and substance.
A pension, located in Badacsonytomaj, actually had only three rooms, and up to ten people could spend the night. However, the bill mentioned a hundred and thirty customers.
In their accounts, neither the name of Jobb Jövőért nor the name of Hoppá appeared, according to the information given to the prosecutor.
Győző Farkas, the company's manager, told the hvg.hu website that when the prosecutors summoned him and showed him the invoices, he immediately knew that they were false documents.
"The name of our company and our tax number were placed in a bad place on the seal."
He added: "Beyond the shape, the fact that according to the invoice, a hundred people stayed there, did not collide either, since this facility only has eleven rooms, which do not have as much space.
In addition, the bill also mentions meals, and our restaurant has been closed for a long time."
The issuers of zero invoices have also not been informed about Budapest's travel agencies, which are part of their choice, but only organizing travel abroad. So, naively, they have indicated stays in Hungary on invoices to be paid in cash, which also goes against the agency's accounting practices.
They also added VAT to these documents, as the survey revealed, while travel activities benefits, the destination of which is outside the European Union, are invoiced without VAT.
Similarly, the VAT rate of the four invoices established on behalf of the Hotel Revfülöp in the order of Jobb Jövőért was incorrect, since the company's benefits did not support a 25% VAT as indicated, but a 15% VAT. Furthermore, the hotel employees only issued printed invoices, while the fakes were handwritten.
The prosecution's investigation reveals that the "issuers" also made errors by mentioning as a provision the transport of goods by road, that the invoice company could not exercise, since its profile was the investment council.
Moreover, it is also for vices of forms, such as types of inadequate invoices and false stamps, that invoices issued in the order of Együtt a Harmadik Évezrédért Alapítvány, of XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont have proved false.
As in the case of Ravenna Bt. or Kunfehértó's sports internship, which both deny being the authors of the invoices issued on their behalf.
Neither did the falsaries pay attention to the fact that HIB Kft., established in Nyíregyháza, was in liquidation at the time (in 2001) the group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület was supposed to have a meal at their home. According to our information, it is for this reason that the liquidator of the company refused to issue this invoice.
Deliberate invoices
Another category of invoice issuers is that of those who were fully aware that they were asked to issue fictional invoices.
The foundation Esély Budapestért Alapítvány, at the request of the group of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták, established an invoice at the order of the foundation Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, for a sum of HUF four million.
According to the indictment, the company manager Collab Kft. was led to issue false invoices by one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi.
Similarly, it has cooperated with the Zuschlags, the company Biogate Kft., which is currently under liquidation and which in 2003 issued invoices at the order of the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány Foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület Association and the association Vörösfenyő Egyesület, for an amount of about five million HUF, but behind which no benefit has actually been provided.
There was no financial movement, either, since the invoices issued were subsequently cancelled, but the agencies did not mention it in their accounts.
The next category of companies issuing invoices is that of companies directly related to the accused.
For example, the administrative delegate of the CEO of Delta Trió Kft., dealing with fuel trade and automobiles, whose headquarters was in Budapest, but where it was found, was Ivan Kubatov.
In October, November and December 2005, the company issued several invoices for the sale of computer equipment, amounting to approximately HUF 18 million.
According to the investigation, these equipment would have been purchased by the Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which had been in liquidation since September 14, 2005.
The director of this company was a man of Romanian origin, to whom Iván Kubatov would also have sent documents related to the company, between 2002 and 2005.
According to what we know, Kubatov acknowledged during the investigation that he issued invoices in the order of the companies Atlasz, Hoppá and Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, and that he damaged their countervalue.
It is precisely at Ivan Kubatov's request that Romanian Masons created Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
In fact, none of these companies were working, which the accused explained by the fact that they were not receiving work.
He also used these companies, since, at the request of Master Zsolt Szente, co-author and editor of the founding acts of the companies, he established invoices to their names, in order of associations related to Zuschlag, such as the Atlasz and Y-Generáció associations.
Kubatov gave organizations, 15 total invoices, issued by Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, for a value of HUF 14.2 million.
The parquet thought that 10% of the amounts indicated on the invoices as well as VAT went into Kubatov's pocket.
Man even used the company Szi-Beri Bt. to establish fictional invoices that were used as part of Biztos Pont's grant application.
In January 2006, the Y-Generáció and Szövetség Association in Modern Magyarországert filed a grant application with the public utility organization of the Socialist Party, Tánciscos Mihály Alapítvány (TMA).
They obtained this subsidy for a two-fold amount of HUF 500,000, but these amounts were not used for the objectives indicated in the application.
To avoid this, five fictitious invoices received from the company Works Team Kft. were submitted to the TMA.
Furthermore, these invoices were found during the search conducted in the office of Árpad Kemecsei, Ministry of Education.
At the hearing, a part of the accused will report the method of making invoices, as she had already done before the prosecution.
What could be really interesting would be that the main accused, János Zuschlag himself, decides to lift the veil over the whole story.
So far, his confessions are not very detailed, and although he has promised several times to tell the least details, he has not yet done so.
The question is whether it is in his interest, or if so, the Socialists would have concluded an agreement that, in exchange for the reimbursement of much of the 50 million HUF, Zusi alone would bear the hat.
Today, the latter is probably vexed, since applications for his supervised residence, based on a reduction in his detention conditions, are continually falling into the ear of a deaf person.
While those who have caused much more damage, and the perpetrators of non-reparable economic crimes, walk freely or at least, wait at their own home at the end of the proceedings. He does not have this possibility.
The psychology of the auction: why do we spend more money?
In auction sales, buyers tend to spend more and overestimate the goods.
New York University researchers in neurology and economics have succeeded in updating the neurological and economic bases of this known and apparently irrational behaviour.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be distanced from this type of competition, such as sales on eBay auctions, and that is why they prefer to even pay too high a price.
These researches have attempted to develop a neurological scheme of this kind of "game" using sales at experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the loto, while the other group took part in a sale for playful auctions, while using a functional magnetic resonance (RMF) process, researchers analyzed the active brain areas of experimental subjects.
In both games, the participants could earn money, but during the sale to auctions whose essential element is the oversale of a third party, the whole under the brain stem, called striatum, was moving intensively during the loss of the part.
This part of the brain, alongside several other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-stimulation" of the nervous system.
That is why, according to researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the leak in the face of the violent reaction of the stratum.
In support of their theories, the economic members of this group of researchers continued financial surveillance analyses.
In these cases, three groups were over-employed against one partner, under various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and did so.
In another group, they promised that if, in addition, they would get out of the party, then they would receive an additional $15 in reward.
While the third group received $15 before the auctions, the group members also lost that money, in case they lost the auctions.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the emphasis was placed at home on victory, while at home on failure.
In this way, demonstrating the assumption of neurologists, the members of the player team "against failure" were willing to be placed higher than those performed by the control group and the "for victory".
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
In fact, each of them did not explain the phenomena found in auction sales only by the pleasure of winning and the parade in front of the risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped to remove the contradiction between the two theories, resulting in a third explanation." - Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economic Sciences at the University of New York, found.
Hepatitis: When should we consult a doctor?
Around the world, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while chronic liver disease is mentioned among the first causes of death in Hungary.
One hundred miles are estimated to be the patients with the hepatitis virus in Hungary, but only seven miles follow treatment, which is because the patients often do not know they are the carriers of the virus.
Hepatitis is a generic name given to liver-affected infections caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and yellowness are characteristic, but pathogens and diseases generated differ from one another.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogens, are spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tube (e.g. food or contaminated water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses by blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, it is in any case recommended to get vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no vaccine against C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consumption of contaminated foods, usually accompanied by a poor general condition, weakness, stomach and nausea.
Then it develops on the skin and on the white of the eye a visible yellowish, the saddles become clearer and the urine takes a darker color. Healing can take two to three weeks.
Around the world, every year, one million people die of the most serious form of this pathology, such as liver cancer or cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that according to estimates, only one in ten patients receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if it is not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients are not aware of the virus, because the pathogen destroys liver cells in a subtle way. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular testing tests.
Contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently, there are 200 million patients with chronic type C hepatitis worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult with its physician treating symptoms of unknown origin.
The disease can be cured if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, thus the risk of infection disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30 is the World Day of Hepatitis, organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing patients in all four corners of the world.
Its objective is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does he who grows up in God feel less pain?
According to the results of a recent research, religious belief would function as a kind of analgesic, which would have already contributed to making the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British daily Telegraph published an article according to which researchers from the University of Oxford realized an interesting experience by analyzing how much belief in God could influence tolerance to the pain of the human being.
As part of this experience for the least bizarre, 12 Catholic believers and so many atheists were subjected to electrochocs, while each of them observed a painting representing the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude much of the suffering.
Thanks to a technique of palpation of the human brain, it was also discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for pain regulation.
This analysis is the first of a series of experiences, where academics, scholars, philosophers and theologians participate from different areas of the university.
Specifically, the experience takes place in the following way: an instrument emitting sparks and spreading the electrochocs is fixed on the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experience to keep a close look at two paintings, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady with hermine painted by Leonard de Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers at the origin of this experience hoped that the vision of the Virgin Mary would evoke a kind of state of faith among believers, while the choice of the painting of Da Vinci, not much different from the first, was about its soothing effect.
Experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during this time, they received 20 electrochocs in four successive parts, while looking either at the painting on a religious theme or the one on a more general theme.
Catholics said that in the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt like "safe," as someone we "take care of" and they "calmed, and peace invaded them."
In view of the painting of religious theme, they reported 12% pain less than when looking at the work of Leonard.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, believes that we can achieve the same effects with any other strong image, in the atheists, provided we find the appropriate photo.
"We should find an image in which they react very positively, such as a mother or father," said the psychologist.
Tom Wright, Anglican bishop, welcomed the results of these research.
"The practice of faith should change and in many cases, it actually changes our personality," Wright added.
After these excellent results, there is only the question of what would be the effect on the regulation of the pain of subjects if a Madonna painted by Leonard or by a painter of the same size were shown to believers?
Would the view of a virgin Mary of better quality lead to better results?
