The intelligent car imitates the flight of the boulder
What method would be better to develop technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, if it is not the imitation of an existing obstacle detector in nature?
Like bees.
In the amazing project presented at the CEATEC, which took place in Japan, bourbon bees gave the strategic idea of departure to Nissan's engineers, to inspire them on how they should design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired self-robotized control system, type BR23C, which he has equipped with bee qualities, the ultimate objective being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee is its own space, of oval shape, which actually resembles a lot of our safe protection shell - Kazuhiro Doi, the director of the research and development department and the technological public relations of the brand, explained.
The bee's face-eye plays a key role, as it is capable of seeing in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To imitate the facet-eye functions, engineers addressed the idea of laser telemeter.
It identifies the obstacles in an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of BR23C, evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the microprocessor, which transforms it into avoidance maneuver immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini auto robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it from a sufficient angle to avoid the collision.
Unlike any existing system, this avoidance maneuver is carried out in an instinctive manner.
"If it wasn't so, the mini auto robot couldn't react fast enough to avoid the obstacle," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotized car project.
It must react instinctively and instantly, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and internal layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for the moment the collision is considered inevitable.
This whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bee.
The process must take place at a glance.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can only be of two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can rotate.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees have to avoid other bees, in our case, we could only use the rotating movement, acceleration as well as slowing down as maneuvers available to the mini auto robot
BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and whose energy concentration is greater, which makes their life longer than in the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is paramount, not data processing, and even less the ability to store.
This mechanism should only treat a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It is not necessary to store and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilo-bytes of continuous memory.
We don't need memory of a giga-byte capacity, or even mega-bytes.
This is the first step towards designing an instant avoidance technology. According to Nissan's estimates, this system will make its way into the cars manufactured in series in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on his way.
