Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 per cent compared to the month of August 2007 - communicated to the Central Office of Statistics of Hungary.
Industrial export prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, while compared with those of a previous year, they decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of the fluctuations in domestic prices and exports, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to those in the previous month, and by 3.2 per cent compared to those in the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices have increased to a lesser extent: 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industry were only slightly increased by 0.1 per cent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and shoe manufacturing sector ( 2.8 per cent), with first, the manufacture of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, then the production of shoes with 2.5 per cent monthly increase.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical and chemical manufacturing sector (1.6 per cent).
A deflation resulted in the oil processing sectors (1.4 per cent), the manufacture of machinery and electrical appliances (0.9 per cent), as well as a minimum increase in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing have not changed.
Other sectors of the processing industry have increased from 0.2% to 0.9%.
In the supply of electricity, gas, steam and water sectors, representing a significant weight in the national industrial operation, prices increased by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in the price of gas established by the authorities since 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison, taking into account the domestic sales of the processing sectors, prices in the oil processing sector have been the most significant increase (32.4%).
In the manufacturing of metal products, prices were increased by 13.2 per cent, while in the important area of food production, beverages and tobacco, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price decreases have occurred in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of machinery and electrical appliances (0.3 per cent).
In the other sectors of the processing industry, the price increase rose from 0.6 per cent to 9.1 per cent.
Prices in the processing industry as a whole increased by 10.2 per cent during the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded 18.7 per cent in the previous year.
Among the domestic trade groups and by sector allocation in August were the investment-initiating sectors that showed the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and material sectors for subsequent processing had no change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase was observed in the energy and material production sectors for further processing (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, 6.8 per cent inflation was measured, while for the profit-initiating sectors, a 1.4 per cent decrease was measured.
Industrial export prices in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, while they fell by 3.9 per cent over 12 months.
In one month, our national means of payment fell by 1.7 per cent compared to the euro, and by 7.1 per cent compared to the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it increased by 7.5 per cent compared to the euro and by 15.9 per cent compared to the dollar.
