Mp3 player pointed at the finger, they put the hearing at risk.
Listening to music at full volume for an extended period using portable musical devices such as Mp3 readers can cause permanent damage to the hearing.
This is what the European Commission announces, which, in a press release in Brussels, cites the opinion of the Scientific Committee on the unforeseen and recently identified health risks (Csseri) of the EU, published today.
"of this scientific report - let us read in the note - it appears that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to full volume music using portable musical devices, for more than one hour per week, are at risk of permanent loss of hearing capacity."
"I'm concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable musical devices and mobile phones at full volume can unconsciously damage their hearing in an irreparable way," says Meglena Kuneva.
"According to scientific data - the responsible EU continues - this is a clear risk and we need to react quickly.
The most important thing is to raise awareness of consumers and make this information public.
We must also re-examine existing control systems in view of scientific opinion, so that they are fully effective and can follow new technologies."
Brussels called on the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise generated by them.
"Scientists-conclude the EU-executive confirm that there is good reason to worry, and that the European Commission will now examine with the Member States and other interested parties what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents, against exposure to noise from portable musical devices and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100Db, but there is a growing concern about hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to well limit these data using solutions such as reducing levels and duration of exposure to noise.
The Scientific Committee Ue notes that users of portable musical devices, who listen to full-volume music (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours per week, exceed the current limits on the maximum level of noise agreed at the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions during prolonged periods are at risk of permanent loss of hearing capacity after 5 years.
This is of interest to 5-10% of the users of these devices, and their number can be quantified around 2.5 million and 10 million people in the U.S.
