The super glue to walk on the walls.
Conquer the laws of gravity thanks to a super glue and, in the future, walk on walls like Spiderman.
This is the goal of various American research centres, and today, a team of four institutes has almost succeeded.
With a adhesive measuring only 2.5 square centimeters, researchers managed to keep a body of 100 kilograms attached to a vertical wall.
The U.S. Science magazine published the findings of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the team of researchers, is an evolution of those we know who use a specific carbon structure, called nano carbon tubes.
"The glue principle can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged like a pile of spaghetti." Explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology of Atlanta.
Scientists have been inspired by the legs of the geckos, covered with microscopic hairs that make it possible to ensure the animal, a perfect adherent.
Tests on various materials, such as glass, Téflon, and glass paper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles, and at the same time, that it "is easily detached from the wall" explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton Engineering.
"This material could be used as a temporary adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
Can it be to walk on walls like Spiderman? Maybe yes, but researchers think of a much less fascinating use such as the connection between electronic devices, since carbon nano tubes are heat conductors and electric current.
Other applications could concern aerospace engineering.
For now, no superheroes.
THE OTHER RESEARCH- The University of Berkeley, California, is also seeking new membership.
In an article by the American Chemical Society, Californian researchers presented an adhesive made up of microfibres such as hair, which self-cleans dust during the movement on a surface to ensure a perfect and constant adherence.
