Students victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for one room.
The student rental market was not aware of a crisis
According to Sunia's last survey, renting a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 euros in Florence, 650 euros in Naples, 600 euros in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects at the point of exclusion of the whole categories of young people, of the right to study because of the very high overall costs that families of origin have to support - explains the head of the study office of Sunia, Laura Mariani- in these cities, the high demand by students has distorted the market so that a process of generalized increase has even begun for residents.
In most cases, rental offers also include a series of violations: free-type contracts, unregistered, rent-free, sub-allocations.
For Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the revision of tax taxation are necessary to calm prices.
Reading in detail the investigation, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes approximately 450 euros; for a single room, we go from 650 euros minimum (Black Band area), to an average value of 800 (Lambiate, Udine, and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 euros (Vittoria area)
In Florence, an average bed costs 350/400 euros, a room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in areas close to the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a double bed, and 370 to 500 for a simple room.
In Rome, in the areas close to central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), approximately 600 euros are required for a simple one, 450 for a bed in a double.
Values slightly lower (550 euros for a simple one) for areas close to other universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
You can save only if you move away to the peripheral areas: 300 euros for a bed, and 450 for a simple one in the Predestina, Centocella or similar area.
In Naples, for a bed it takes 300/400 euros, for a simple one, we spend 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the areas Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, for bed, you have to count 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a simple one.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they are of major importance in the city economy.
Finally, cities such as Perugia, where rentals are often taken by extra-Community students, there is a subsequent anomaly: the rent requested to foreign students is increased by 25/30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Adieu old cinema Paradiso, the cities eliminate historical halls.
Historical cinemas close in favor of the Multiplex.
"A city without cinema is a blind city, it's like a face without eyes"
The image offered by the stagemaker Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates well what is happening in the great Italian urban centers, but also in the cities of the province,
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth on the periphery of the great multisalles, and the death of consumption of mono rooms in the central areas of the cities, is one of the major events that appears to us ineligible and indisputable; in addition it has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historical places and charged with memory, "it's as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a piece of track and so much emotion," observes the director of the New Cinema Paradise, which offers to Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prix of the Cannes jury, and who reported the poetry of a province hall, and the nostalgia of a way to live the cinema, lost can be forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main trader association, mean everything: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and these are the rooms of the main cities that paid the costs mostly: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the areas most affected by the closure, Emilie Romaine is leading 82 single cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The evidence confirming that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-threaded cinemas: 195 screens plus in Lombardy over the past five years, 81 in Tuscany as well as in Emilie-Romagna.
"Italian exploitation has grown irrationally," observes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it is also necessary to guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a firm room in a city, these visitors are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplex.
Not to mention the lack of deliberation of the credit for traders: the previous debt of the State is about EUR 10 million.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, it would take between €16 million and €18 million a year.
We note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city which, concerned by these closures, decided to resolve the situation by signing a protocol between Mayory and Anec, the first such in Italy, to defend and promote the cinemas mono rooms of historic and periphery centers.
Among the proposed regulations, there are tax facilities for managers and benefits to the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area, and will have special parking rates and certain parking lots.
"It's an initiative that pleases" observes Giuseppe Tornatore "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna putting in place other measures.
However, it is clear that, in contrast to the super power of multiplex, traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, as today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that, for me, has always been important: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Cinema Paradise" to which I had been thinking for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass by the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have had so many shared emotions, I turn from the other side to not see the black panels through the dust.
