When energy comes from waves, the big ones are now launching.
This is an over-measured deposit that occupies more than 70% of the planet's surface and now the world's largest energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources on which colosses like Chevron have set their eyes, and now try to put their hands on them.
The possibility of obtaining energy from sea movements has been studied for hundreds of years now, and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research has intensified.
When the oil price dropped, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was set aside, but now the environmental authorities and the new increase in oil give a great boost to the sector
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London in 2007 estimated that 15% of the global electricity need could be covered by offshore operating systems.
That would be twice the amount produced by nuclear power plants.
And besides, there would be currents and tides..
Colosses to the attack.
The first company to put on marine energy was the Energy, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build an installation in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, we would have said a real revolutionary step.
Two years from this, more and more candidates among these companies that have always been dedicated to traditional energy focus on marine energy.
